  {
    "client_msg_id": "dc9cf2e0-8a58-4bc9-8cf9-83a0181933ec",
    "type": "message",
    "text": "<@UC2A2ARPT> I think graph based domain modelling is indeed in some sense natural and the predominant organizing model in most of knowledge representation, but something tells me that there are alternative models with better trade-offs. Check out those pattern generators by Grenander. You Hest is also a very welcome change in the way we directly manipulate behaviour on screen. Really great job on building something like that.\n\nNow that image is from a paper I stumbled on about managing complexity called \"Systems Theoretic Techniques for Modeling, Control and Decision Support in Complex Dynamic Systems\" It has got more cool images: <https://arxiv.org/pdf/1008.0775.pdf> And I think he does indeed think of the predominant model as another graph instead of being a tree with cross references.\n\nMy only gripe with such a model is that once you bring in time to track the topological changes, it quickly has a chance to devolve into a messy hairball that then displays multiple conformations over time, to which the only sane approach is to divide it into domains of interest and then inspect the pieces one by one.\n\nI am thinking out loud what other units of composition might be out there to build systems up from scratch and what kind of trade offs they might have.",
    "user": "UDKTZSD6H",
    "ts": "1562349815.194900",
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
